:eyetype
1,almond (almond-shaped)
2,banjo (wide, circular eyes)
3,beady (small and round)
4,bug (protuding)
5,bulging
6,bullish (a descriptive term; fierce)
7,button (small and round or large and round)
8,close-set (eyes that are set close together but not quite crossed)
9,crescent (half-moon shaped, either naturally or when grinning)
10,cross-eyed
11,cue ball (very large, bulging eyes)
12,deep-set (set deeply into the skull, most pronounced with a prominent forehead ridge)
13,dewdrop (the shape of a teardrop)
14,egg-shaped (large ovoid)
15,esotropic (a form of strabismus in which one eye is turned or crossed inward toward the nose)
16,exophthalmic (eyes that bulge from their sockets, usually due to a thyroid condition)
17,exotropic (a form of strabismus in which one eye is turned or crossed outward, away from the nose)
18,falcon (a descriptive term; a small, round dark eye; bird-like)
19,feline (cat-like, with lentil-shaped pupils)
20,fish (glassy and emotionless)
21,gimlet (piercing; penetrating)
22,glassy (dull)
23,goggle (prominent or bulging; also rolling eyes)
24,hollowed eye sockets (a descriptive term for deep-set eyes, most likely to appear in people who are anorexic or malnourished)
26,hooded (lids covering part of half of the eyes; sleepy-eyed or bored eyes)
27,kidney-shaped (reniform, occurring naturally when smiling)
28,lentil, lenticular (shaped like a lentil or bioconvex lens; the most common eye shape)
29,luminous (a descriptive term for an animal's eyes when reflecting light at night; the reflective eye layer itself is called the <i>tapetum</i>)
31,lunulate (crescent-shaped)
32,Oriental (slanted)
33,owlish (wide, round and alert)
34,pea (tiny and round)
35,pop (protuberant or bulging)
36,puffin-like (in the shape of a teardrop)
37,rheumy (watery, moist)
38,saucer (large or goggle-like)
39,shark-like (cold and indifferent)
40,slanty (Oriental)
41,slits (narrow)
42,sloe (large and dark, or almond-shaped)
43,spaniel (round and moist)
44,squinty (near-sighted or far-sighted)
45,strabismus (the condition of squinting)
46,sunken (deep eye sockets, an effect that accompanies anorexia or malnourishment)
47,walleyed (large, glossy eyes; also, an eye that turns outward, or a whitish or light-colored iris)
48,wide-set (set far apart under the forehead)

:eyecolor
1,acorn (weathered nut-brown)
2,autumn leaf (reddish-brown to brown)
3,biscuit (light toasted brown)
4,bronze (reddish-brown or coppery brown)
5,burnt almond (dark brown)
6,camel (medium brown)
7,Congo (muddy or dark brown, after the African river)
8,dun (dull grayish-brown)
9,dusky (dark, shadowy, as in deepening twilight)
10,dusty road (light brown if dry, dark brown after a rain shower)
11,earth (broad variability, the entire spectrum of brown)
12,ebony (very dark brown or black)
13,elk (medium to dark brown)
14,fawn (pale, yellowish-brown)
15,fox (reddish-brown)
16,Grand Canyon (broad variability, from light to dark browns to reddish-browns)
17,grizzly bear (variable; brownish, grayish or yellowish)
18,gunmetal (black)
19,hawk brown (yellowish-brown, medium brown or grayish-brown)
20,hazel (reddish-brown or yellowish-brown, usually flocked with green or gray)
21,honey (yellowish-brown or golden brown)
22,humus (rich soil brown; dark brown or black)
23,kelp (seaweed brown)
24,leather (medium to dark brown; reddish-brown)
25,lentil (light to medium brown)
26,lignite (brownish-black)
27,mahogany (dark reddish-brown or yellowish-brown)
28,mill pond (deep brown or black)
29,mink (dark brown)
30,Mississippi (muddy brown, as found in parts of the river)
31,mocassin (same as leather; medium to dark brown; reddish-brown)
32,molasses (usually dark brown)
33,mottled (flecked, streaked, spotty or blotchy)
34,mud (broad variability, from light to dark red)
35,Nubian (medium brown)
36,nut-brown (broad variability, from eyllowish-brown to dark brown)
37,obsidian (very dark or black)
38,olive (dark brown or black)
39,otter (medium to dark brown)
40,raisin (reddish-brown or black)
41,raven (black)
42,Rio Grande (muddy)
43,russet (yellowish-, or reddish-brown)
44,sandy (yellowish, grayish or medium brown)
45,sienna (yellowish-brown; burnt sienna is reddish-brown)
46,soot (grayish-brown or black)
47,sorrel (light brown or light reddish-brown; dried autumn leaf)
48,sparrow brown (grayish-brown)
49,tarnished penny (reddish-brown)
50,taupe (dark brownish-gray; moleskin)
51,tawny (brownish-yellow or tan)
52,umber (the color of shadow)
53,weathered acorn (medium brown)
54,apple green (light green)
55,azure (sky blue)
56,baby blue (very light to very pale greenish- or purplish-blue)
57,bittersweet nightshade (purplish-blue, similar to pasisonflower)
58,blueberry (light to medium blue)
59,blue jay (light blue)
60,bottle green (dark to grayish-green)
61,celestial blue (sky blue)
62,cobalt (deep, vivid blue; also strong greenish-blue)
63,cornflower (blue or purple)
64,denim (the color of jeans)
65,dove gray (grayish-blue or grayish-brown)
66,electric blue (bright neon blue)
67,emerald (strong yellowish-green)
68,gentian (blue)
69,grape (blue or purple)
70,holly green (medium to dark green)
71,hyacinth (deep purplish-blue to vivid violet)
72,ice (very light blue)
73,indigo (dark blue to grayish, purplish-blue)
74,iridescent (having rainbow-like or shifting colors, depending on the angle they're seen from)
75,iris (light purple)
76,jade (pale green)
7,jungle (leaf green)
78,kingfisher (blue-gray)
79,lagoon blue (broad variability, from light, crystal blue to dark blue)
80,lagoon green (broad variability,  from light to dark green)
81,lapis lazuli (sky blue to deep blue)
82,larkspur (blue to medium blue)
83,lavender (pale to light purple or very light, very pale violet)
84,lightning (thunderbolt blue; light, silvery blue)
85,lilac (pale or light to medium purple)
86,mauve (brilliant violet or purple, or medium reddish-purple)
87,midnight blue (very dark blue)
88,misty blue (very light blue)
89,morning glory (purplish-blue)
90,moss (medium to dark green)
91,Nordic blue (light to medium blue)
92,olive green (light to medium green)
93,passionflower (purplish-blue)
94,peacock blue (medium to dark or strong greenish-blue)
95,pea green (yellowish-green)
96,periwinkle (purplish-blue)
97,plum (dark blue to deep reddish-purple)
98,powder blue (medium to pale blue, or purplish-blue)
99,Prussian blue (medium to dark blue)
100,rainforest green (misty leaf green)
101,royal purple (medium to strong violet, or deep purple)
102,sapphire (blue)
103,sea green (broad variability, medium to very dark green)
104,sea smoke (very light silvery blue or gray)
105,sky blue (also known as azure)
106,slate (dark gray to bluish-gray)
107,smoke (gray-blue)
108,smoked glass (gray or dark gray)
109,snow shadow (shadowy blue)
110,star (twinkling light blue or green)
111,steel (dark gray to purplish-gray)
112,storm sea (very dark blue to dark gray)
113,teal (medium or dark bluish-green to greenish-blue)
114,terre verte (French term for "green earth"; an olive green)
115,twilight (dark purple)
116,violet (reddish-blue to purplish-blue)
117,Virginia bluebell (blue to purplish-blue)
118,wild lupine (light to medium blue)
119,wisteria blue (purplish)

