:nose
1,Aquiline nose (hooked or curved, like an eagle's beak)
2,Arabian nose (long and broad)
3,Bob nose (knoblike)
4,Boxer's nose (broken, misshapen)
5,Bulbous nose (large, shaped like a bulb)
6,Button nose (round and small)
7,Chisled nose (giving the appearance of plastic surgery)
8,Corrected and pampered nose (formed by a plastic surgeon)
9,English nose (long and narrow)
10,Eskimo nose (broad and narrow)
11,Flaring nose (flaring nostrils)
12,Gourdlike nose (misshapen, warty or gnarled, like a gourd)
13,Gumdrop nose (small and dainty)
14,Hawk nose (aquiline)
15,Hog-nosed nose (like a pig's snout)
16,Hooked nose (curved, aquiline)
17,Jewish nose (prominent)
18,Negroid nose (broad, with flaring nostrils)
19,Potato nose (very large and misshapen, like an Idaho potato)
20,Prissy nose (high-cut nostrils)
21,Pug nose (short, flattened and somewhat turned up at the end)
22,Retrousse nose (turned up at the tip)
23,Rhinophyma nose (a red and grossly enlarged nose; a disorder of alcoholics and people from the British Isles; also known as rum nose, rummy nose, toper's nose, and whiskey nose)
24,Roman nose (having a high, distinctive bridge)
25,Rosacea nose (a skin condition causing reddening of the nose, most commonly found in alcoholics, people from the British Isles, and people who flush easily)
26,Ruddy nose (reddish-colored)
27,Skewed nose (crooked)
28,Snub nose (short and turned up; pug)
29,Turned-up nose (retrousse; turned up at the tip)
30,Whiskey nose (a red and grossly enlarged nose; a disorder of alcoholics and people from the British Isles; also known as rum nose, rummy nose, and toper's nose)

:beard
1,A la Souvaroff beard (a mustache/beard in which the mustache is joined to the sideburns and the chin is left clean-shaven)
2,Anchor beard (a short, pointed beard worn at the edge of the chin with a fringe extending up to the center of the bottom lip)
3,Assyrian beard (a long beard with plaits or spiral curls)
4,Barbiche beard (a small tuft of hair under the bottom lip; also known as a barbula)
5,Belgrave beard (a neatly groomed, medium-length beard that may be cut round, square, or with a point)
6,Burnside beard (the mustache joined with the sideburns and the jaw left clean-shaven; named after General Ambrose Burnside in the nineteenth century)
7,Cadiz beard (a pointed, medium-length beard, originating in Spain)
8,Cathedral beard (a full, blowing beard that splits like a fish tail at the bottom, worn by the clergy in mid sixteenth to the seventeenth centuries)
9,Ducktail beard (a long, slender, neatly-trimmed beard, reminiscent of the tail of a duck)
10,Dundreary whiskers (sideburns grown long and left to hand off the sides of the face while the chin is left clean-shaven)
11,Fish-tail beard (a full, blowing beard that splits like a fish tail at the bottom, worn by the clergy in mid sixteenth to the seventeenth centuries)
12,Five o'clock shadow (subtle or light stubble growth found on most men's faces at the end of the day)
13,Forked beard (a beard cut or combed into two branches or wisps; also known as a swallowtail)
14,Goatee (a small, pointed beard, resembling that of a goat)
15,Grizzled, or grizzly beard (gray or flecked with gray)
16,Imperial beard (a long tuft of hair extending down from beneath the lowerlip; made famous by Napoleon III in 1839)
17,Jewish beard (a long, full, untrimmed beard, as that prescribed in the book of Leviticus; also known as a Hebraic beard)
18,Lincolnesque beard (a medium-length beard worn with sideburns but no mustache; made famous by Abraham Lincoln)
19,Miami Vice beard (the unshaven look, more than five o'clock shadow but less than a beard, popularized by the 1980s cop show)
20,Muttonchops (thick sideburns trimmed to resemble mutton chops)
21,Old Dutch beard (a short, square-cut beard with a clean-shaven upper and lower lip)
22,Olympian beard (a very long, thick beard)
23,Paintbrush beard (a very small, pointed beard worn on the botton of the chin, reminiscent of the tip of a paintbrush)
24,Peach fuzz (light, pubescent whiskers)
25,Pencil beard (a pencil-width of whiskers extending from the bottom lip to the chin)
26,Raleigh beard (a pointed beard with the facial portion closely cropped; named after Sir Walter Raleigh)
27,Rat's nest beard (a descriptive term for an uncombed or ungroomed beard; also described as a bird's nest)
28,Roman T beard (a small, rectangular chin tuft that, in conjunction with a rectangular mustache, forms the configuration of the letter T)
29,Satyric tuft (a chin tuft, named after Satyr, the half-goat, half-man from Greek mythology)
30,Screw beard (a short, slender beard that is twisted or twined, popular in the seventeenth century; may be used to denote any twisted beard)
31,Shenandoah beard (a spade-shaped beard)
32,Spade beard (a pointed or rounded beard, reminiscent of the shape of a spade)
33,Square-cut beard (a medium of long beard cut square or flat on the bottom)
34,Steel wool beard (a descriptive tern for a tough, wiry beard)
35,Stiletto beard (a long, slender, pointed beard)
36,Swallowtail beard (a forked beard, reminiscent of the tail of a swallow)
37,Tile beard (a long or short square-cut beard)
38,Trojan beard (a thick, curly beard of medium length)
39,Uncle Sam beard (the beard sytle worn by the U.S. cartoon figure)
40,Van Dyke beard (a short, pointed beard without sideburns)
41,Viking beard (any long, flowing beard reminiscent of the ancient Norsemen)

:mustache
1,A la Souvaroff mustache (a style characterized by a clean-shaven chin and a mustache joined to the sideburns)
2,Boxcar mustache (a rectangular style with square ends, like a railroad car)
3,Chevron mustache (an inverted V)
4,Clark Gable mustache (a neat, thin line)
5,Cookie duster mustache (humorous descriptive term for a mustache)
6,Fu Mancho mustache (long, thin drooping mustache worn with a narrow beard)
7,Handlebar mustache (a long, thick mustache with ends turned up to resemble the handlebars of a bicycle)
8,Hindenburg mustache (a very long, thick mustache with turned-up ends)
9,Horseshoe mustache (an inverted <i>U</i> or horseshoe-like mustache that droops down over the chin)
10,Kaiser mustache (a mustache with turned-up ends; popularized by Germany's Kaiser in 1914)
11,Mistletoe mustache (a narrow mustache in the configuration of two crescents, reminiscent of mistle leaves)
12,Pencil line mustache (a very narrow mustache, sometimes divided with a space at the center of the lip)
13,Pyramid mustache (a triangular mustache)
14,Rat's nest mustache (descriptive term for an unkempt mustache)
15,Regent mustache (a neat mustache resembling the letter <i>M</i> with rounded peaks)
16,Roman T mustache (s style comprised of a rectangular mustache and a narrow chin tuft, forming the configuration of the letter <i>T</i>)
17,Soupstrainer mustache (a thick, huge mustache allowed to grow over the upper, and sometimes even the lower, lip)
18,Squarebutton mustache (a short square or rectangle of bristles, as worn by Adoplh Hitler and Charlie Chaplin)
19,Toothbrush mustache (a short square or rectangle of bristles, as worn by Adoplh Hitler and Charlie Chaplin)
20,Walrus mustache (a thick, huge mustache allowed to grow over the upper, and sometimes even the lower, lip; humorously known as a soupstrainer)
21,Waxed mustache (any mustache with curled tips, twiddled and held together with wax)
22,Wings mustache (a neatly trimmed mustache resembling the wings of a bird)
23,Wings of a B-52 mustache (a broad inverted <i>V</i>, like the wings of the classic bomber)

